                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I am getting pretty tired of the people who talk about how hard it was in the old days, and how people today don't know how to play their class.  Wow.  I'll bet you walked 15 miles to school each way, uphill, in 32 feet of snow, without shoes -- and felt you were lucky to do it!  Golly, it must have been tough...
<br />

<br />
I started EQ last March.
<br />

<br />
When I did LOIO, I was alone.  I charm soloed Lavastorm and Oasis for an eternity, and never had a group.  I partnered with a SK for Paw, but we were alone.  When I did LGuk, there were 2 or 3 farmers there and nothing else.  In Seb, there was one other, but he was afk (botted).
<br />

<br />
Yeah, it was possible to find groups -- PC and the Kunark Express of OT and DL.  However, I did not have SoL until level 24, so I had already been charm soloing for 12 levels.  I did not learn the "haste, clarity, tash, slow" routine until after I was already used to hunting yellows solo.  In addition, groups occasionally turned me away at 30, citing my untwinked cloth armor pieces and cracked staff.  It was fun when I would decide to solo right next to them, and outperform them...
<br />

<br />
Does LDoN make dungeon crawls easier than the olde days?  LDoN doesn't have repops behind you like you did back in the olde days of SolA -- but when I was doing SolA last May, I had to charm solo.  So is it really any easier than the olde days?  In addition, if you are moving at a speed that's appropriate for a LDoN, the repops won't have time to spawn anyway...
<br />

<br />
When I read here about enchanters that never started using charm until 64th level, my jaw drops.  I am not trying to offend, and if I grouped through my whole career, doing buffing, debuffing, and crowd control, I may never have had a use for charm either.  But I didn't.  I started late, and, therefore, soloed 75% of my time.  That meant charm.
<br />

<br />
I get into LDoN groups and pull out charm, and people get nasty with me -- and there is usually someone who leveled an enchanter as their main in "ye olde-school methode" who tells me it's too difficult to maintain the charm, etc.  I end up nearly outdamaging my group (I would outdamage if I hasted my pet, but I don't want to risk the "told you so" of my groupmates), while still taking care of CC, buffs, and debuffs.  I've not had any complaints about my CC capabilities, and it's a rare thing that I am oom before the cleric...  So, which player really knows the class?
<br />

<br />
Internet guides, mudflation in the bazaar, the availability of buffs in PoK (I was level 30 before I purchased PoP -- doh!), and maps all make the early levels easier, but does it make up for the things that make it harder?  More importantly, does it make for a poorer player?  Not in my experience...
<br />

<br />
Meschaelene
<br />

<br />
This is a rant that was originally part of the "Does LDoN make for better players" thread, and there are some references to that thread.  Then, I realized it was ranty, so I posted it here, instead.
<br />

<br />
