                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Things are just different now.
<br />

<br />
I recently re-started leveling my rogue, and unless I want to do the /snore of DL, DSP and other assorted zones, I have to solo.  I'm sure that is the case of your chanter as well.
<br />

<br />
One of the few times I was grouped with my rogue, the chanter in the group said, "its too hard to target in here" (LDoN), and I immediately offered 2 or 3 ways he can target faster.  I than mentioned using color stuns, which he scoffed at, "I'm using fascination, its the same thing"  I tried explaining to him the difference and advantages of each line of spell,  but after he made it clear he wasnt willing to listen I just gave up.
<br />

<br />
You are sound like a good new chanter. The guy my rogue ran into is atm a poor to moderate new chanter. He did not have any CC skills, and did not charm. You have learned a skill at level 4, that I did not take the time to learn until level 65; as long as you eventually learn both skillsets, what difference does order matter?
<br />

<br />
People have charm solo'd to level 50 (and beyond) since EQ began. Charm was always recognized as the most powerful spell in EQ (CH and slow are 2nd and 3rd, cant decide which is which). However, what is an acceptable risk to you, once upon a time was not acceptable.  Unfortunately for you, the option of grouping starting in your low 20s as all but evaporated. The few times at those levels you do get a group, it is often because the other players are so unskilled they cannot pull their own weight. (but that is another rant)</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=293448" target="_blank" class="postlink">Abitoo</a>
