                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">-One is that people at that point didn't really understand how important hps were to a caster. Out of ignorance most enchanters were a lot wimpier than they are today.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Bit more to it than that.  Back then hp gear pretty much didn't exist.  You had Djarn's Amethyst Ring (think that was the name, 80 hp, 9 agil), jade bracers (after the jewelry revamp), and the ranged item from the giants.  That was about it and two of those were uber loot at the time.  Added to that, back then, there was a cost to be paid.  For me, to wear my defensive orientated stuff, little as it was, I paid a price in int and cha.  Today, it's A and B.  Back then, it was A or B.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It's not that being a newer player makes you bad, it's that the game has evolved to the point that bad players can still enjoy the game and advance.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Disagree...it's not that bad players can advance, they've always been able to.  It's that there's very little advantage to being good.  Good used to provide you dungeon groups, where you got the loot that made you better still.  Now, you buy better stuff in the bazaar, so why bother to go into those dungeons?  The biggest problem with loot inflation, really...the loot you can get at your level is no longer relevant and that removed the primary reason people did dungeons.  Nothing I'd like better than to see every last item in EQ get a respectable required level to wear, based upon where it came from.  There's just no incentive to get good, no cost to staying bad.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
