                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Seems they touched a raw nerve.  First, I agree with Airif.  Second, just because we were forced to do things differently does not make you a better player.
<br />

<br />
I learned to charm fairly early.  I also learned to use my animation, basically soloing my way to the low 50s.  Without the hps that enchanters have today, we normally didn't charm indoors (also, no focus items).  When Sol A was still experience, it was considered a lower-level guild raid zone -- and what is left to rot on corpses today was an upgrade to the players.  At the time, the only thing standing between a successful Sol A raid and a total wipe was the skill of the enchanters and monk.  A level 24 enchanter nowdays has more hit points than our main tank on those raids (banded + a few bronze pieces).  We did things differently, based on the environment.  That seems to me to be a definition of a good player.
<br />

<br />
OK, all posturing aside, the <span style="font-weight: bold">big</span> difference between then and now is how the zones are viewed.  We actually wore items that dropped in the zones we raided, whether Sol A or Dalnir or City of Mist.  Now, there is nothing worth keeping -- not even twink gear.  Today, the zones are merely a way to get experience, maybe farm a little plat.
<br />

<br />
"Old School" and "New School" are different.  I don't consider either to be better or worse, just different.  The environment is different.  Dungeons (beginning with Warrens) don't have the big trains or the older dungeons.  It was a joy to see a couple of enchanters lock down a train of 10-12 in Chardok, but mostly the rule was to move slowly enough that you don't ever pull that many (tanks didn't last as long, either).  Lull didn't work at the time, other than to use as a pulling spell (it always failed).  But, that is the joy I see being an old timer.
<br />

<br />
Many newer enchanters can function in the new-style dungeons without really learning crowd control.  I think these are the people that players think of when they think of clueless enchanters.
<br />

<br />
Of course, being an old-timer, you can discount my ramblings.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=37024" target="_blank" class="postlink">Serius</a>, Enchanter to King Tearis Thex on the Luclin Server
<br />
