<br />
I never had money for it until the mid 30's anyway, and the amount I made was just a little over what I spent on the buffs.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>AbitooXev wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Rez's.  Remember, making the 20min run at level 16 from your bind to your camp?  Not anymore, cause clerics can start 0% rez, and the graduations between 0-50 and 90 are alot smoother.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I always bound pretty close, anyway.  I had one early CR in the Qeynos sewer when I was bound in Toxx.  I learned my lesson (I hated that boat) and still make a practice of binding closeby.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>AbitooXev wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Travel.  Try doing the Wind of Tashani quest without using pok books or Nexus. Also, try doing the stein of moggok (chanter right of passage) without using newer forms of travel.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Travel is easier.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>AbitooXev wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Binds.  Melee characters can bind easily in many more zones than was previously available.  Little effect for casters.  Classic example would be the barbarian warrior who now can bind at the wayfarer camp, right next to his slaughter area.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I have no newbie experience playing a melee.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>AbitooXev wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Twink groups.  Gone are the days of trying to teach 5 others how to work with a chanter, usually. Also, these characters tend to have the best gear money can buy, and the best buffs their mains and other bots can provide.  They tend to group still for exp bonus and because they miss the social nature of the game.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Twink groups are terrible -- the absolute worst!  They wake mezz constantly, and since they can take the hits without a problem, it's only the new player that feels the pain.  The twinks do not learn, since it does not hurt them.  Plus, I find that twink groups are "relaxing" from their "real" characters -- just the sort of group I like to trust my character to.  So, the newbie character dies, and the rest of the group is unaffected.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>AbitooXev wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">What's harder?
<br />
Groups are harder to find.
<br />
Play skill in said groups is argueably lower because of previously mentioned advantages.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
OK -- we have travel and a bag.  Most everything else you have said applies only to twinks, which are different from new players.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>AbitooXev wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Now despite how unbalanced my list seems,  I am not going to pass judgement.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I think you are too late.
<br />

<br />
I'd like to also point out that many of the quests you could do, I could not.  They required a group to take out a few targets, and I could not find one.  You also did not have death helping you convince your group members to assist!
<br />

<br />
But here's the argument that it's harder now.  Other people here have written that, in the "olde" days, it was not "worth it" to use charm or charm solo.  Now, even after the charm nerfs, and the group xp bonuses, and the "theoretically" better twinks that may populate your group, I had to level up with charm solo.  So, it wasn't worth it then, and it has been heavily nerfed, but it's now worth it.  If you think about it, this says a lot about groups and the new player's experience.
<br />

